10 . About DEXA 99 1 Description The development of the cyberspace society and the increasing use of multimedia technology will influence how society access to cultural material . In this context , the QPMIDS workshop seeks to bring together all major players : users such as museums , and cultural heritage holders , researchers and industrial developers working in the field of distributed multimedia information systems to assess the state of the art and practical solutions in multimedia cultural applications , and also to introduce promising future research issues such as real-time multimedia data processing , virtual one-line multimedia management , or multimedia distance learning systems . The topics of the workshop cover advanced multimedia and hypermedia computing technologies for cultural multimedia applications such as tourism , digital libraries , digital archive and virtual museums where new approaches to support on-line accesses to information are needed . The explosion in volume and complexity of digital information that people want to access and analyse influences the evolution of the multimedia distributed systems . The kinds of data referred to by 'multimedia data' expand . Still images , texts , and hypermedia books were included in this category , several years ago . Recently , moving pictures , especially video , audio , as well as 3 D objects in virtual realities are added in the list . Several issues still need to be tackled in order to meet the challenge of the multimedia . As a first issue , improving the quality of the stored data , on easing and speeding up processing and retrieving , and editing these data adequately by distant users . The second issue is concerned with Web-based and presentation-based applications and distributed multidimensional multimedia systems . The data and users are distributed over computer networks and real-time data transfer is required . So good quality transfer of data among them is needed . The integration of emerging standards such as CORBA or java RMI may provide new communication capabilities in order to increase QoS inside distributed multimedia systems . The third issue is the system architecture issue ( distributed shared memory , load balancing algorithm , . . . ) . Current systems are insufficient to support the management of multimedia data owning to their time-sampled nature . Problems such as data placement , buffer management , admission control and load balancing still exist . The extension of the database systems to support distributed multimedia applications thus require new mechanisms to ensure the synchronized presentation of multimedia data exchanges and also to ensure copyrighting and multimedia information protection .
2 . Topics of Interest Topics of interest include , but are not limited to : . Modeling of multimedia and hypermedia data . Multimedia database architecture . Distributed multidimensional multimedia information systems . Distributed and parallel multimedia query processing and query optimization . QoS ( load balancing , data placement ) issues in multimedia information system . Virtual reality management . Multimedia distance learning system . Standards and language for multimedia information / database systems . Benchmarking of distributed multimedia systems . Multimedia and Media Mining . Copyright and protection of the multimedia and hypermedia information 3 . Submissions Short original contributions or demonstration regarding the problem solving and / or aims for further research activities in the workshop topics are welcome . Extended abstract papers or position papers should be in English and not exceed 5 double spaced pages or 1000 words . The cover page should include the title , name and affiliation of the author ( s ) , contact , address , email , fax and telephone . Final paper should not exceed 10 single spaced pages . Papers and demonstration summary should be sent electronically ( postscript ) not later than
